<text top="2659" left="770" width="649" height="50" font="font1" id="p1_t81" reading_order_no="82" segment_no="11" tag_type="text">weeks  working  undercover  in  Afghani- </text>
<text top="2702" left="771" width="648" height="51" font="font4" id="p1_t82" reading_order_no="83" segment_no="11" tag_type="text">stan,  drawing  on  his  old  tribal  networks </text>
<text top="2747" left="771" width="647" height="50" font="font1" id="p1_t83" reading_order_no="84" segment_no="11" tag_type="text">and  recruiting  chieftains  to  join  the  battle. </text>
<text top="2791" left="772" width="647" height="50" font="font1" id="p1_t84" reading_order_no="85" segment_no="11" tag_type="text">His  strategy  was  to  sever  the  Taliban  from </text>
<text top="2838" left="771" width="648" height="46" font="font6" id="p1_t85" reading_order_no="86" segment_no="11" tag_type="text">its  tribal  links,  winning  over  local  chiefs </text>
<text top="2877" left="770" width="650" height="51" font="font4" id="p1_t86" reading_order_no="87" segment_no="11" tag_type="text">with  promises  of  peace  and  international </text>
<text top="72" left="1472" width="647" height="50" font="font1" id="p1_t87" reading_order_no="88" segment_no="3" tag_type="text">aid.  Karzai’s  men  advanced  from  Uruzgan, </text>
<text top="119" left="1472" width="648" height="46" font="font6" id="p1_t88" reading_order_no="89" segment_no="3" tag_type="text">north  of  Kandahar;  on  the  other  side  of  the </text>
